{"title_page": "Songs of Innocence and of Experience", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{About|William Blake's poems|albums by this name|Songs of Innocence and of Experience (disambiguation)}}{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=May 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n[[File:Songs of Innocence and of Experience, copy AA, object 1.jpg|thumb|''Songs of Innocence and of Experience Shewing the Two Contrary States of the Human Soul'' title page]]\n'''''Songs of Innocence and of Experience'''''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Songs of Innocence and of Experience, copy C, 1789, 1794  (Library of Congress): electronic edition|url = http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/copyinfo.xq?copyid=songsie.c|website = www.blakearchive.org|accessdate = 2015-11-05|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043747/http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/copyinfo.xq?copyid=songsie.c|archivedate = 2016-03-04}}</ref> is a collection of illustrated poems by [[William Blake]]. It appeared in two phases: a few first copies were printed and [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] by Blake himself in 1789; five years later he bound these poems with a set of new poems in a volume titled ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience Shewing the Two Contrary States of the Human Soul''. Blake was also a painter before the creation of ''Songs of Innocence and Experience'' and had painted such subjects as [[Oberon]], [[Titania]], and [[Puck (folklore)|Puck]] dancing with fairies.<!--- maybe so, but not mentioned or sourced in article main body and of debatable relevance? -->\n\n\"Innocence\" and \"Experience\" are definitions of consciousness that rethink [[John Milton|Milton]]'s existential-mythic states of \"Paradise\" and \"Fall\". Often, interpretations of this collection centre around a mythical dualism, where \"Innocence\" represents the \"unfallen world\" and \"Experience\" represents the \"fallen world\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Fearful Symmetry|last=Frye|first=Northrop|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1969|isbn=0-691-01291-1|location=Princeton, New Jersey|pages=[https://archive.org/details/fearfulsymmetrys0000frye_7/page/42 42]|url=https://archive.org/details/fearfulsymmetrys0000frye_7/page/42}}</ref> Blake categorizes our modes of perception that tend to coordinate with a chronology that would become standard in [[Romanticism]]: childhood is a state of protected [[innocence]] rather than [[original sin]], but not immune to the fallen world and its institutions. This world sometimes impinges on childhood itself, and in any event becomes known through \"experience\", a state of being marked by the loss of childhood vitality, by fear and inhibition, by social and political corruption and by the manifold oppression of Church, State and the ruling classes. The volume's \"Contrary States\" are sometimes signalled by patently repeated or contrasted titles: in ''Innocence'', ''Infant Joy'', in ''Experience'', ''Infant Sorrow''; in ''Innocence'', ''The Lamb'', in ''Experience'', ''The Fly'' and ''The Tyger''. The stark simplicity of poems such as ''The Chimney Sweeper'' and ''The Little Black Boy'' display Blake's acute sensibility to the realities of poverty and exploitation that accompanied the \"[[And did those feet in ancient time|Dark Satanic Mills]]\" of the [[Industrial Revolution]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Broadview Anthology of British Literature: The Age of Romanticism|year=2010|publisher=Broadview Press|isbn=978-1-55111-404-0}}</ref>\n\n==''Songs of Innocence''==\n{{redirect|Songs of Innocence}}\n'''''Songs of Innocence''''' was originally a complete work first printed in 1789. It is a conceptual collection of 19 poems, engraved with artwork. This collection mainly shows happy, innocent perception in pastoral harmony, but at times, such as in \"[[The Chimney Sweeper]]\" and \"[[The Little Black Boy]]\", subtly shows the dangers of this na\u00efve and vulnerable state.\n\nThe poems are each listed below:\n{{div col}}\n:[[Introduction (Songs of Innocence)|Introduction]]\n:[[The Shepherd (Blake) |The Shepherd]]\n:[[The Echoing Green]]\n:[[The Lamb (poem)|The Lamb]]\n:[[The Little Black Boy]]\n:[[The Blossom]]\n:[[The Chimney Sweeper]]\n:[[The Little Boy Lost]]\n:[[The Little Boy Found]]\n:[[Laughing Song]]\n:[[A Cradle Song]]\n:[[The Divine Image]]\n:[[Holy Thursday (Songs of Innocence)|Holy Thursday]]\n:[[Night (Blake)|Night]]\n:[[Spring (Songs of Innocence)|Spring]]\n:[[Nurse's Song]]\n:[[Infant Joy]]\n:[[A Dream (Blake)|A Dream]]\n:[[On Another's Sorrow]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==''Songs of Experience''==\n{{Redirect|Songs of Experience}}\n'''''Songs of Experience''''' is a poetry collection of 26 poems forming the second part of [[William Blake]]'s ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''. The poems were published in 1794 (see [[1794 in poetry]]).  Some of the poems, such as \"The Little Girl Lost\" and \"The Little Girl Found\", were moved by Blake to ''Songs of Innocence'' and were frequently moved between the two books.<ref group=note>[http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/work.xq?workid=songsie&java=no See the various extent editions republished in their original publication order] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113195544/http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/work.xq?workid=songsie&java=no |date=2013-11-13 }} at the [[William Blake Archive]].</ref>\n\nThe poems are listed below:\n{{div col}}\n:[[Introduction (Blake, 1794)|Introduction]]\n:[[Earth's Answer]]\n:[[The Clod and the Pebble]]\n:[[Holy Thursday (Songs of Experience)|Holy Thursday]]\n:[[The Little Girl Lost]]\n:[[The Little Girl Found]]\n:[[A Dream (Blake)|A Dream]]\n:[[Nurse's Song]]\n:[[The Sick Rose]]\n:[[The Fly (poem)|The Fly]]\n:[[The Angel (Songs of Experience)|The Angel]]\n:[[The Tyger]]\n:[[My Pretty Rose Tree]]\n:[[Ah! Sun-flower]]\n:[[The Lilly (poem)|The Lilly]]\n:[[The Garden of Love (poem)|The Garden of Love]]\n:[[The Little Vagabond]]\n:[[London (William Blake poem)|London]]\n:[[The Human Abstract (poem)|The Human Abstract]]\n:[[Infant Sorrow]]\n:[[A Poison Tree]]\n:[[A Little Boy Lost]]\n:[[A Little Girl Lost]]\n:[[To Tirzah]]\n:[[The School Boy]]\n:[[The Voice of the Ancient Bard]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Musical settings==\n{{see also|William Blake in popular culture}}\n{{refimprove-section|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Blake Experience 29.jpg|thumb|Blake's title plate (No.&nbsp;29) for ''Songs of Experience'']]\nPoems from both books have been set to music by many composers, including [[Ralph Vaughan Williams]], [[Joseph Holbrooke]], [[John Frandsen (composer)|John Frandsen]], [[Per Drud Nielsen]], [[Sven-David Sandstr\u00f6m]], [[Benjamin Britten]], and [[Jacob ter Veldhuis]]. Individual poems have also been set by, among others, [[John Tavener]], [[Victoria Poleva]], [[Jah Wobble]], [[Tangerine Dream]], [[Jeff Johnson (musician)|Jeff Johnson]], and [[Daniel Amos]]. A modified version of the poem \"The Little Black Boy\" was set to music in the song \"My Mother Bore Me\" from Maury Yeston's musical [[Phantom (musical)|Phantom]]. The folk musician [[Greg Brown (folk musician)|Greg Brown]] recorded sixteen of the poems on his 1987 album ''[[Songs of Innocence and of Experience (Greg Brown album)|Songs of Innocence and of Experience]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gregbrown.org/gbdisco.html#blake |title=Greg Brown Discography |publisher=Gregbrown.org |accessdate=2012-11-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201090107/http://www.gregbrown.org/gbdisco.html#blake |archivedate=2012-12-01 }}</ref> and by Finn Coren in his ''Blake Project''. \n\nThe poet [[Allen Ginsberg]] believed the poems were originally intended to be sung, and that through study of the rhyme and metre of the works, a Blakean performance could be approximately replicated. In 1969, he conceived, arranged, directed, sang on, and played piano and harmonium for an album of songs entitled ''[[Songs of Innocence and Experience by William Blake, tuned by Allen Ginsberg]]'' (1970).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://writing.upenn.edu/pennsound/x/Ginsberg-Blake.php |title=PennSound: Ginsberg/Blake |publisher=writing.upenn.edu |accessdate=2012-11-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112095948/http://writing.upenn.edu/pennsound/x/Ginsberg-Blake.php |archivedate=2012-11-12 }}</ref>\n\nThe composer [[William Bolcom]] completed a setting of the entire collection of poems in 1984. In 2005, a recording of Bolcom's work by [[Leonard Slatkin]], the Michigan State Children's Choir, and the University of Michigan on the Naxos label won four [[Grammy Awards]]: Best Choral Performance, Best Classical Contemporary Composition, Best Classical Album, and Best Producer of the Year (classical).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.music.umich.edu/about/BolcomGrammy.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221041527/http://www.music.umich.edu/about/BolcomGrammy.pdf |archivedate=2011-02-21 }}</ref>\n\nThe composer [[Victoria Poleva]] completed \"Songs of Innocence and of Experience\" in 2002, a chamber cycle on the verses by Blake for soprano, clarinet and accordion. It was first performed by the ensemble Accroche-Note of France.\n\nThe Swedish composer David Unger<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidunger.n.nu|title=David Unger, s\u00e5ngare, s\u00e5ngpedagog, komposit\u00f6r, m.m.|website=www.davidunger.n.nu|accessdate=9 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503190033/http://www.davidunger.n.nu/|archivedate=3 May 2016}}</ref> completed \"Night songs op. 24\", a setting of five poems from Songs of Innocence for solo voice and piano in 2013. It was first performed by baritone Anthony Schneider and pianist Rosemary Barnes in Vienna, Austria the same year. \n\nPopular group [[Tangerine Dream]] based their album ''[[Tyger (album)|Tyger]]'' on lyrics by William Blake.\n\nPopular rock group [[U2]] released an album called ''[[Songs of Innocence (U2 album)|Songs of Innocence]]'' in 2014, and followed it in 2017 with ''[[Songs of Experience (U2 album)|Songs of Experience]]''.\n\n[[Karl Jenkins]]' Motets includes a setting of The Shepherd.\n\nThe fictional rock band Infant Sorrow, as featured in the 2008 film ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]]'', appears to be named after the Blake poem.\n\n==Facsimile editions==\n\nThe [[Huntington Library and Art Gallery]] in San Marino, California, published a small facsimile edition in 1975 that included sixteen plates reproduced from two copies of '''''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''''' in their collection, with an introduction by James Thorpe. The songs reproduced were ''Introduction'', ''Infant Joy'', ''The Lamb'', ''Laughing Song'' and ''Nurse's Song'' from ''Songs of Innocence'', and ''Introduction'', ''The Clod & the Pebble'', ''The Tyger'', ''The Sick Rose'', ''Nurses Song'' and ''Infant Sorrow'' from ''Songs of Experience''.  Tate Publishing, in collaboration with The William Blake Trust, produced a folio edition containing all of the songs of Innocence and Experience in 2006. A colour plate of each poem is accompanied by a literal transcription, and the volume is introduced by critic and historian [[Richard Holmes (biographer)|Richard Holmes]].{{fact|date=February 2014}}\n\nWilliam Blake, ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience'' edited with an introduction and notes by Andrew Lincoln, and select plates from other copies.  Blake's Illuminated Books, vol. 2.  William Blake Trust / Princeton University Press, 1991.  Based on King's College, Cambridge, copy, 1825 or later.\n\n''Songs of Innocence''  Dover Publications, 1971.  Based on copy of Lessing J. Rosenwald Collection, Library of Congress, Copy B, ca. 1790.\n\n''Songs of Experience''  Dover Publications, 1984.  Based on \"a rare 1826 etched edition,\" per back cover.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group = note}}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|Songs of Innocence|''Songs of Experience''}}\n*[http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/work.xq?workid=songsie&java=no Multiple digital copies of Blake's illustrated versions of the ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''] at the [[William Blake Archive]]\n*[http://www.rarebookroom.org/Control/blkin1/index.html ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''] (1794), from [[Rare Book Room]]\n*[http://www.rarebookroom.org/Control/blkin2/index.html ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''] (1826), from [[Rare Book Room]]\n*[http://writing.upenn.edu/pennsound/x/Ginsberg-Blake.php Link to Ginsberg recordings of the poems]\n* {{librivox book | title=Songs of Innocence and of Experience | author=William Blake}}\n\n{{William Blake|lit}}\n{{Artists' books}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:English poetry collections]]\n[[Category:Artists' books]]\n[[Category:English art]]\n[[Category:Self-published books]]\n[[Category:1789 poetry books]]\n[[Category:1794 poetry books]]\n[[Category:Songs of Innocence and of Experience| ]]\n[[Category:Books about cats]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{About|William Blake's poems|albums by this name|Songs of Innocence and of Experience (disambiguation)}}{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=May 2015}}\n{{refimprove|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n[[File:Songs of Innocence and of Experience, copy AA, object 1.jpg|thumb|''Songs of Innocence and of Experience Shewing the Two Contrary States of the Human Soul'' title page]]\n'''''Songs of Innocence and of Experience'''''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Songs of Innocence and of Experience, copy C, 1789, 1794  (Library of Congress): electronic edition|url = http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/copyinfo.xq?copyid=songsie.c|website = www.blakearchive.org|accessdate = 2015-11-05|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304043747/http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/copyinfo.xq?copyid=songsie.c|archivedate = 2016-03-04}}</ref> is an illustrated collection of poems by [[William Blake]]. It appeared in two phases. A few first copies were printed and [[Illuminated manuscript|illuminated]] by William Blake himself in 1789; five years later he bound these poems with a set of new poems in a volume titled ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience Shewing the Two Contrary States of the Human Soul''. William Blake was also a painter before the songs of innocence and experience and made paintings such as Oberon, Titania, and Puck dancing with fairies.\n\n\"Innocence\" and \"Experience\" are definitions of consciousness that rethink [[John Milton|Milton]]'s existential-mythic states of \"Paradise\" and \"Fall\". Often, interpretations of this collection centre around a mythical dualism, where \"Innocence\" represents the \"unfallen world\" and \"Experience\" represents the \"fallen world\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Fearful Symmetry|last=Frye|first=Northrop|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=1969|isbn=0-691-01291-1|location=Princeton, New Jersey|pages=[https://archive.org/details/fearfulsymmetrys0000frye_7/page/42 42]|url=https://archive.org/details/fearfulsymmetrys0000frye_7/page/42}}</ref> Blake categorizes our modes of perception that tend to coordinate with a chronology that would become standard in [[Romanticism]]: childhood is a state of protected [[innocence]] rather than [[original sin]], but not immune to the fallen world and its institutions. This world sometimes impinges on childhood itself, and in any event becomes known through \"experience\", a state of being marked by the loss of childhood vitality, by fear and inhibition, by social and political corruption and by the manifold oppression of Church, State and the ruling classes. The volume's \"Contrary States\" are sometimes signalled by patently repeated or contrasted titles: in ''Innocence'', ''Infant Joy'', in ''Experience'', ''Infant Sorrow''; in ''Innocence'', ''The Lamb'', in ''Experience'', ''The Fly'' and ''The Tyger''. The stark simplicity of poems such as ''The Chimney Sweeper'' and ''The Little Black Boy'' display Blake's acute sensibility to the realities of poverty and exploitation that accompanied the \"[[And did those feet in ancient time|Dark Satanic Mills]]\" of the [[Industrial Revolution]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Broadview Anthology of British Literature: The Age of Romanticism|year=2010|publisher=Broadview Press|isbn=978-1-55111-404-0}}</ref>\n\n==''Songs of Innocence''==\n{{redirect|Songs of Innocence}}\n'''''Songs of Innocence''''' was originally a complete work first printed in 1789. It is a conceptual collection of 19 poems, engraved with artwork. This collection mainly shows happy, innocent perception in pastoral harmony, but at times, such as in \"[[The Chimney Sweeper]]\" and \"[[The Little Black Boy]]\", subtly shows the dangers of this na\u00efve and vulnerable state.\n\nThe poems are each listed below:\n{{div col}}\n:[[Introduction (Songs of Innocence)|Introduction]]\n:[[The Shepherd (Blake) |The Shepherd]]\n:[[The Echoing Green]]\n:[[The Lamb (poem)|The Lamb]]\n:[[The Little Black Boy]]\n:[[The Blossom]]\n:[[The Chimney Sweeper]]\n:[[The Little Boy Lost]]\n:[[The Little Boy Found]]\n:[[Laughing Song]]\n:[[A Cradle Song]]\n:[[The Divine Image]]\n:[[Holy Thursday (Songs of Innocence)|Holy Thursday]]\n:[[Night (Blake)|Night]]\n:[[Spring (Songs of Innocence)|Spring]]\n:[[Nurse's Song]]\n:[[Infant Joy]]\n:[[A Dream (Blake)|A Dream]]\n:[[On Another's Sorrow]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==''Songs of Experience''==\n{{Redirect|Songs of Experience}}\n'''''Songs of Experience''''' is a poetry collection of 26 poems forming the second part of [[William Blake]]'s ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''. The poems were published in 1794 (see [[1794 in poetry]]).  Some of the poems, such as \"The Little Girl Lost\" and \"The Little Girl Found\", were moved by Blake to ''Songs of Innocence'' and were frequently moved between the two books.<ref group=note>[http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/work.xq?workid=songsie&java=no See the various extent editions republished in their original publication order] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113195544/http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/work.xq?workid=songsie&java=no |date=2013-11-13 }} at the [[William Blake Archive]].</ref>\n\nThe poems are listed below:\n{{div col}}\n:[[Introduction (Blake, 1794)|Introduction]]\n:[[Earth's Answer]]\n:[[The Clod and the Pebble]]\n:[[Holy Thursday (Songs of Experience)|Holy Thursday]]\n:[[The Little Girl Lost]]\n:[[The Little Girl Found]]\n:[[A Dream (Blake)|A Dream]]\n:[[Nurse's Song]]\n:[[The Sick Rose]]\n:[[The Fly (poem)|The Fly]]\n:[[The Angel (Songs of Experience)|The Angel]]\n:[[The Tyger]]\n:[[My Pretty Rose Tree]]\n:[[Ah! Sun-flower]]\n:[[The Lilly (poem)|The Lilly]]\n:[[The Garden of Love (poem)|The Garden of Love]]\n:[[The Little Vagabond]]\n:[[London (William Blake poem)|London]]\n:[[The Human Abstract (poem)|The Human Abstract]]\n:[[Infant Sorrow]]\n:[[A Poison Tree]]\n:[[A Little Boy Lost]]\n:[[A Little Girl Lost]]\n:[[To Tirzah]]\n:[[The School Boy]]\n:[[The Voice of the Ancient Bard]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Musical settings==\n{{see also|William Blake in popular culture}}\n{{refimprove-section|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:Blake Experience 29.jpg|thumb|Blake's title plate (No.&nbsp;29) for ''Songs of Experience'']]\nPoems from both books have been set to music by many composers, including [[Ralph Vaughan Williams]], [[Joseph Holbrooke]], [[John Frandsen (composer)|John Frandsen]], [[Per Drud Nielsen]], [[Sven-David Sandstr\u00f6m]], [[Benjamin Britten]], and [[Jacob ter Veldhuis]]. Individual poems have also been set by, among others, [[John Tavener]], [[Victoria Poleva]], [[Jah Wobble]], [[Tangerine Dream]], [[Jeff Johnson (musician)|Jeff Johnson]], and [[Daniel Amos]]. A modified version of the poem \"The Little Black Boy\" was set to music in the song \"My Mother Bore Me\" from Maury Yeston's musical [[Phantom (musical)|Phantom]]. The folk musician [[Greg Brown (folk musician)|Greg Brown]] recorded sixteen of the poems on his 1987 album ''[[Songs of Innocence and of Experience (Greg Brown album)|Songs of Innocence and of Experience]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gregbrown.org/gbdisco.html#blake |title=Greg Brown Discography |publisher=Gregbrown.org |accessdate=2012-11-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121201090107/http://www.gregbrown.org/gbdisco.html#blake |archivedate=2012-12-01 }}</ref> and by Finn Coren in his ''Blake Project''. \n\nThe poet [[Allen Ginsberg]] believed the poems were originally intended to be sung, and that through study of the rhyme and metre of the works, a Blakean performance could be approximately replicated. In 1969, he conceived, arranged, directed, sang on, and played piano and harmonium for an album of songs entitled ''[[Songs of Innocence and Experience by William Blake, tuned by Allen Ginsberg]]'' (1970).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://writing.upenn.edu/pennsound/x/Ginsberg-Blake.php |title=PennSound: Ginsberg/Blake |publisher=writing.upenn.edu |accessdate=2012-11-07 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112095948/http://writing.upenn.edu/pennsound/x/Ginsberg-Blake.php |archivedate=2012-11-12 }}</ref>\n\nThe composer [[William Bolcom]] completed a setting of the entire collection of poems in 1984. In 2005, a recording of Bolcom's work by [[Leonard Slatkin]], the Michigan State Children's Choir, and the University of Michigan on the Naxos label won four [[Grammy Awards]]: Best Choral Performance, Best Classical Contemporary Composition, Best Classical Album, and Best Producer of the Year (classical).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.music.umich.edu/about/BolcomGrammy.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221041527/http://www.music.umich.edu/about/BolcomGrammy.pdf |archivedate=2011-02-21 }}</ref>\n\nThe composer [[Victoria Poleva]] completed \"Songs of Innocence and of Experience\" in 2002, a chamber cycle on the verses by Blake for soprano, clarinet and accordion. It was first performed by the ensemble Accroche-Note of France.\n\nThe Swedish composer David Unger<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidunger.n.nu|title=David Unger, s\u00e5ngare, s\u00e5ngpedagog, komposit\u00f6r, m.m.|website=www.davidunger.n.nu|accessdate=9 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503190033/http://www.davidunger.n.nu/|archivedate=3 May 2016}}</ref> completed \"Night songs op. 24\", a setting of five poems from Songs of Innocence for solo voice and piano in 2013. It was first performed by baritone Anthony Schneider and pianist Rosemary Barnes in Vienna, Austria the same year. \n\nPopular group [[Tangerine Dream]] based their album ''[[Tyger (album)|Tyger]]'' on lyrics by William Blake.\n\nPopular rock group [[U2]] released an album called ''[[Songs of Innocence (U2 album)|Songs of Innocence]]'' in 2014, and followed it in 2017 with ''[[Songs of Experience (U2 album)|Songs of Experience]]''.\n\n[[Karl Jenkins]]' Motets includes a setting of The Shepherd.\n\nThe fictional rock band Infant Sorrow, as featured in the 2008 film ''[[Forgetting Sarah Marshall]]'', appears to be named after the Blake poem.\n\n==Facsimile editions==\n\nThe [[Huntington Library and Art Gallery]] in San Marino, California, published a small facsimile edition in 1975 that included sixteen plates reproduced from two copies of '''''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''''' in their collection, with an introduction by James Thorpe. The songs reproduced were ''Introduction'', ''Infant Joy'', ''The Lamb'', ''Laughing Song'' and ''Nurse's Song'' from ''Songs of Innocence'', and ''Introduction'', ''The Clod & the Pebble'', ''The Tyger'', ''The Sick Rose'', ''Nurses Song'' and ''Infant Sorrow'' from ''Songs of Experience''.  Tate Publishing, in collaboration with The William Blake Trust, produced a folio edition containing all of the songs of Innocence and Experience in 2006. A colour plate of each poem is accompanied by a literal transcription, and the volume is introduced by critic and historian [[Richard Holmes (biographer)|Richard Holmes]].{{fact|date=February 2014}}\n\nWilliam Blake, ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience'' edited with an introduction and notes by Andrew Lincoln, and select plates from other copies.  Blake's Illuminated Books, vol. 2.  William Blake Trust / Princeton University Press, 1991.  Based on King's College, Cambridge, copy, 1825 or later.\n\n''Songs of Innocence''  Dover Publications, 1971.  Based on copy of Lessing J. Rosenwald Collection, Library of Congress, Copy B, ca. 1790.\n\n''Songs of Experience''  Dover Publications, 1984.  Based on \"a rare 1826 etched edition,\" per back cover.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group = note}}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|Songs of Innocence|''Songs of Experience''}}\n*[http://www.blakearchive.org/exist/blake/archive/work.xq?workid=songsie&java=no Multiple digital copies of Blake's illustrated versions of the ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''] at the [[William Blake Archive]]\n*[http://www.rarebookroom.org/Control/blkin1/index.html ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''] (1794), from [[Rare Book Room]]\n*[http://www.rarebookroom.org/Control/blkin2/index.html ''Songs of Innocence and of Experience''] (1826), from [[Rare Book Room]]\n*[http://writing.upenn.edu/pennsound/x/Ginsberg-Blake.php Link to Ginsberg recordings of the poems]\n* {{librivox book | title=Songs of Innocence and of Experience | author=William Blake}}\n\n{{William Blake|lit}}\n{{Artists' books}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:English poetry collections]]\n[[Category:Artists' books]]\n[[Category:English art]]\n[[Category:Self-published books]]\n[[Category:1789 poetry books]]\n[[Category:1794 poetry books]]\n[[Category:Songs of Innocence and of Experience| ]]\n[[Category:Books about cats]]\n", "name_user": "Martinevans123", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit lead +note", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Songs_of_Innocence_and_of_Experience"}
